We specify prior distributions on the stable parameters α and c, denoted Pr(α) and Pr(c) respectively. We have found that choice of priors on the index of stability have little effect on the ancestral state reconstruction, while the prior on the scale parameter effects the smoothness of the posterior density (Figure 4, right panel). How should we choose appropriate priors for the Monte Carlo simulation? We believe that the Brownian motion model is a useful null model for the evolutionary process. Since the Brownian motion model is a special case of the stable model it is conservative to choose priors that maximize the a priori likelihood of the Brownian model fit. Consider Equations 1 and 5. If we set α=2 and \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
