Our simulation studies indicated that in phylogenetic datasets pD did not increase sufficiently in line with tree size, resulting in over-fitting of stable models on large trees. This is likely because tree size is not incorporated as a component of model complexity in the information criterion. A Bayesian Predictive Information Criterion (BPIC) developed by Ando [personal communication [44]], which amounts to DIC with a increased multiplier on the pD penalty, resolved this problem of over-fitting (see Results below). Specifically, we use the criterion \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}
							$\bar {\mathrm {D}} + 2 p_{D}$
						\end{document}D¯+2pD.
